  <h2 id="mexican-features">Mexican Spanish-Specific Features</h2>

  <p>
    These features are characteristic of Mexican Spanish pronunciation and may differ from other
    Spanish varieties:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Yeísmo:</strong> No distinction between /ʎ/ (as in Peninsular Spanish <em>llover</em>)
    and /ʝ/ or /ʤ/. In Mexican Spanish, both are pronounced as [ʝ] or [ʤ].
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Seseo:</strong> No distinction between /s/ and /θ/. Mexican Spanish uses only [s], never the
    "th" sound [θ] found in Peninsular Spanish.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Consonant Weakening:</strong> Intervocalic consonants (between vowels) are often softened.
    For example, /b/, /d/, /g/ become fricatives [β], [ð], [ɣ] between vowels.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Vowel Devoicing:</strong> In rapid speech, unstressed vowels (especially /i/ and /u/) may
    be partially or fully devoiced, shown with the diacritic [i̥] or [u̥].
  </p>

