  <h2 id="reading-tips">Tips for Reading IPA</h2>

  <p>
    <strong>Start with familiar sounds:</strong> Focus first on symbols that represent sounds similar
    to English. Build confidence before tackling unfamiliar sounds.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Pay attention to stress:</strong> The [ˈ] mark shows which syllable is stressed. Spanish stress
    patterns differ from English, so this is crucial.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Practice syllable by syllable:</strong> Use the [.] syllable boundary markers to break words
    into manageable chunks. Pronounce each syllable separately, then combine them.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Watch for allophonic variation:</strong> The same phoneme may have different pronunciations
    depending on position. For example, /d/ is [d] after /n/ or at the start of a word, but [ð] between
    vowels.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Listen and compare:</strong> When native speaker recordings are available, listen while reading
    the IPA transcription. This reinforces the connection between symbol and sound.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Don't aim for perfection:</strong> IPA helps you approximate authentic pronunciation. Close
    enough is fine - native speakers vary too.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Common Beginner Mistakes</div>
    <p>
      Confusing [b] and [β] - they represent different sounds. [b] is a stop (like English "b"), [β]
      is a fricative (softer, more like "v" but with both lips). Similarly, [d] vs [ð], and [g] vs
      [ɣ]. Position in the word determines which variant is used.
    </p>
  </div>

